ACQUITTED. Released; absolved;
purged of an accusation; judicially discharged from accusation; released from debt, ete.
Includes both civil and criminal prosecutions.
Dolloway vy. Turrill, 26 Wend. (N. Y.) 383,
399. ;

ACTIONARE. L. Lat. (From actio, an
action.) In old records. To bring an action;
to prosecute, or sue. Thorn’s Chron.; Whishaw.

ACTRIX. Lat. A female actor; a female plaintiff. Calvin.


Acts indicate the intention. 8 Co. 146;
Broom, Max. 301.

ADULTER. Lat. One who corrupts;
One who seduces another man’s wife. Adulter solidorum. A corruptor of metals; a
counterfeiter. Calvin.

AGENESIA. In medical jurisprudence.
Impotentia generandi; sexual impotence;
incapacity for reproduction, existing in either sex, and whether arising from structural or other causes.

AGGRIEVED. Having suffered loss or
injury; damnified; injured.


AGGRIEVED PARTY. Under statutes
granting the right of appeal to the party
aggrieved by an order or judgment, the party aggrieved is one whose pecuniary interest is directly affected by the adjudication ;
one whose right of property may be established or divested thereby. Ruff v. Montgomery, 83 Miss. 185, 36 South. 67; McFarland v. Pierce, 151 Ind. 546, 45 N. E. 706;
Lamar v. Lamar, 118 Ga. 684, 45 S. E. 498;
Smith v. Bradstreet, 16 Pick. (Mass.) 264;
Bryant v. Allen, 6 N. H. 116; Wiggin v.
Swett, 6 Metc. (Mass.) 194, 39 Am. Dec. 716;
Tillinghast v. Brown University, 24 R. I. 179,
52 Atl. 891; Lowery v. Lowery, 64 N. C.
110; Raleigh v. Rogers, 25 N. J. Eq. 506. Or
one against whom error has been committed.
Kinealy v. Macklin, 67 Mo. 95.

AMBACTUS.
sent about;
hired out.


A messenger; a servant
one whose services his master
Spelman. ;

AMBIGUITAS. Lat. From ambiguus,
doubtful, uncertain, obscure. Ambiguity;
uncertainty of meaning.

Ambiguitas latens, a latent ambiguity;
ambiguitas patens, a patent ambiguity. See

